column261: * Financial - cuts in public sector spending have resulted in reduced revenue and we will need to downsize and reduce costs across all areas of business to bring expenditure  in line with income.  * Organisational - we will need to remodel delivery of our  front line services to ensure that they are aligned with changing stakeholder priorities. This will mean changes to operational practices and relocation to new premises to improve our efficiency. We will need to focus on change management and service continuity.  * Environmental - we will need to ensure that we have a thorough understanding of the impact of recent legislative and public policy developments in respect of health and welfare to work, and further  developments in personalisation in health and  social care, both locally and nationally. We will need to engage with key decision makers and build  relationships with new commissioning structures such as NHS CCGs in order to position ourselves in the new changing marketplace. And we will also need to adapt our marketing strategies to target personal budget holders as individual customers, as well as commissioners.
column262: Given the extent of change and severity of public sector funding constraints we expect these factors to continue to have a significant impact over the next 2-3 years.

I don't draw down a reduced salary until the end of the financial year - when I am secure in the knowledge that we have sufficient income.
